{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6575973d-f9bc-4084-a781-a4bf25f9374b","content":"These are two distinct C# 15 breaking changes:\n\n---\n\n**Case 1 — `&&` with `dynamic` and user-defined `operator true/false`**\n\n`x && y` is sugar for `T.false(x) ? x : T.&(x, y)`. Previously, when one operand was `dynamic`, the entire expression was deferred to runtime binding.\n\nC# 15 now resolves `operator true`/`operator false` at **compile time** using the static type—even when the other operand is `dynamic`. The compiler sees `IFilter` defines `operator true`/`operator false`, tries to form `&&`, but `IFilter` has no `operator &`, so it fails.\n\n**Fix:** Avoid short-circuit with `dynamic`, or separate the logic:\n\n```csharp\n// Option A: use non-short-circuit &\nvar combined = (dynamic)left & right;\n\n// Option B: explicit short-circuit\nif (!IFilter.operator false(left))\n    combined = (dynamic)left & right;\nelse\n    combined = left;\n```\n\n---\n\n**Case 2 — `ref readonly` lambda return (CS0518)**\n\nCS0518 (\"Predefined type is not defined or imported\") means the compiler needs a framework type that isn't present. C# 15 lambdas with `ref readonly` returns require the compiler to synthesize a delegate with attributes (likely `RequiresLocationAttribute` or a new ref-safety marker) that only ship in the **.NET 11 runtime libraries**.\n\nMost likely cause: you upgraded the **SDK/compiler** to C# 15 but your project still targets an older framework:\n\n```xml\n<!-- Check your .csproj — this must be net11.0 -->\n<TargetFramework>net11.0</TargetFramework>\n```\n\nIf you're already on `net11.0`, verify your SDK installation is complete (`dotnet --info`) and that no stale NuGet package caches are overriding framework assemblies (`dotnet nuget locals all --clear`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"02564a0e-1f70-41bf-b6e0-5c64c929adea","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about two new compiler errors they're getting after upgrading to .NET 11 / C# 15. Let me analyze both cases:\n\n**Case 1: `DynamicOps.cs` - `left && right` with dynamic**\n\nIn C# 15 / .NET 11, there's a breaking change related to how the compiler handles short-circuiting logical operators (`&&` and `||`) when one operand is `dynamic`. \n\nThe `&&` operator requires `operator &`, `operator true`, and `operator false` to be defined. When one operand is `dynamic`, the compiler needs to resolve these at compile time for the static type, but with the introduction of static abstract/virtual interface members and changes to overload resolution with `dynamic`, this scenario has become more strictly checked.\n \nI'm reconsidering the root cause here. The compiler's handling of `dynamic` with user-defined short-circuit operators has likely become stricter in C# 15, where it now validates the static side more rigorously rather than deferring everything to runtime like earlier versions did. can now have static virtual/abstract operators, and the compiler's handling of `dynamic` with these has changed. In newer C# versions, when you use `&&` or `||` with a `dynamic` operand, the compiler now tries to resolve the `operator true` and `operator false` at compile time rather than deferring entirely to runtime. Since `IFilter` defines these as non-virtual static operators that can't be called polymorphically on a `dynamic` value at runtime, this creates a conflict and triggers the error.\n\nFor the `RefHelper.cs` case with `ref readonly` return in lambdas, the CS0518 error suggests a missing framework type. This feature might be new in C# 15 and requires a delegate type or attribute that's only available in newer .NET runtimes—if you're targeting an older runtime, those required types won't be available.\n\nI'm trying to pin down exactly when `ref readonly` returns became supported for lambdas specifically. Methods have had `ref readonly` returns since C# 7.2, and lambdas got explicit return type syntax in C# 10, but the combination for lambdas might need compiler support that depends on a new predefined type like `RequiresLocationAttribute` from .NET 11.\n\nFor the `IFilter && dynamic` case, I'm reasoning through what changed: the interface defines `operator true` and `operator false` as static members, but not `operator &`. Previously with `dynamic` on the right side, the compiler would defer resolution to runtime, but C# 15 likely tightened this to require compile-time resolution of the static operators even when one operand is `dynamic`. the `&&` operator can't be formed. For the second case, the `ref readonly` return type on a lambda likely requires a type that's missing from the target framework—probably something new in .NET 11 that isn't available in the current project setup. The fixes would be either avoiding `&&` with `dynamic` when custom operators are involved, or ensuring the project targets the right framework version with all necessary types available. This could happen if the compiler was upgraded without updating the target framework or if required framework assemblies are missing. Let me look more carefully at the actual code—the interface defines non-virtual static operators on `IFilter`, while `CompositeFilter` implements its own `operator &` along with `operator true` and `operator false`.\n\nWhen calling `Apply` with an `IFilter` and a `dynamic` argument, the `&&` operator needs both an `operator &` and `operator true` for short-circuit evaluation. In older C# versions this whole expression would be dynamic, but in C# 15 the compiler might now try to use the `operator true` from `IFilter` while failing to find a matching `operator &`, causing the compilation to fail.\n\nThe real issue is likely that C# 15 tightened how `dynamic` interacts with user-defined `operator true`/`operator false`. When the static type defines these operators, the compiler faces ambiguity: should it use the compile-time `operator true` for short-circuiting or defer that decision to runtime? This conflict is now rejected as an error.\n\nThe workaround is to use the non-short-circuit `&` operator with dynamic instead, or cast the operands to avoid the ambiguity.\n\nFor the second case with `ref readonly` delegates, the CS0518 error suggests a missing runtime type that C# 15 requires—likely something in `System.Runtime.CompilerServices`. Since the user upgraded to .NET 11 and C# 15, these are new breaking changes introduced by the upgrade itself. The user said they're getting \"new\" errors, which means code that previously compiled is now broken. For the `ref readonly` lambda case, if this is actually a C# 15 feature, then the CS0518 error suggests the project isn't properly configured to target .NET 11 or the necessary type definitions aren't available in the current environment.\n\nLet me think through the two cases more carefully. For the dynamic operator case, C# 15 introduced a breaking change in how `&&` and `||` operators work when one operand is `dynamic` and the other has a static type that defines `operator true` or `operator false` — the compiler now tries to resolve the short-circuit logic statically instead of treating the whole thing as a dynamic operation.\n\nSince `IFilter` doesn't define `operator &`, the `&&` can't be formed. The practical fix is to use the non-short-circuit `&` operator instead, which avoids the compiler trying to apply the short-circuit logic.\n\nFor the `ref readonly` lambda case, the CS0518 error suggests the compiler is looking for a predefined type that isn't available — likely a new delegate type or compiler attribute that C# 15 needs to represent `ref readonly` return lambdas, possibly something in `System.Runtime.CompilerServices`. So the compiler now considers static operators defined on interfaces when resolving compound operators with `dynamic` operands, whereas previously it would either skip interface operators or defer the whole thing to runtime. Since `IFilter` has `operator true` and `operator false` but no `operator &`, the compile-time resolution fails. This is likely a consequence of C# 11's static abstract interface members becoming more mature in the compiler's operator resolution logic.\n\nFor the second case, `ref readonly` return lambdas in C# 15 probably require the compiler to synthesize a delegate type using attributes.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering what's happening with the CS0518 error. The user upgraded to .NET 11, so they should be targeting it, but the compiler can't find a predefined type it needs internally—either a missing framework reference, targeting an older framework, or a corrupted SDK. If `ref readonly` lambdas require the compiler to emit certain synthesized types, those types might not be available in their current setup.\n\nThe real issue is likely that they upgraded the SDK but their project still targets an older framework like net8.0 instead of net11.0, so they have the C# 15 compiler but the old runtime types. The fix is straightforward: update the TargetFramework in their .csproj to net11.0.","outputTokens":4882,"requestId":"B82A:26153C:2CB8826:316EDBE:69FD414E"},"id":"c952cc62-475e-447d-9bb2-37f1cbcb68dc","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:51:47.490Z","parentId":"86192fff-a966-481e-b95f-72f9ddc9ed85"}
